Class Chapter 3 Notes

Selection statements use conditions that are Boolean expressions
A Boolean expression is an expression that evaluates to a boolean value: True or false

- Boolean - wrapper type
- boolean - primitive type

Ex. radius = 5; radius < 0;  // Result = False
Ex. radius = 5; radius >= 0; // Result = True

Ex. double radius = 2.0;
    System.out.println(System.out.println(radius > 0));
    boolean lightsOn = true; // Can either assign as true/false or an expression

An if statement is a construct that enables a program to specify alternative paths of execution
An if statement flowchart consists of a decision-diamond into two branches for true/false into statements

Ex. if (Boolean-expression) { // One way decision structure
        statement for true case
    }

An if-else statement decides the execution path based on whether the condition is true or false

Ex. if (Boolean-expression) { // Two way decision structure
        statement for true case
    } else {
        statement for false case
    }

An if statement can be inside another if statement to form a nested if statement

Ex. if (Boolean-expression) { // First IF
        if (Boolean-expression) { // Second IF
            statement for true case
        }
    } else {
        statement for false case
    }

Common Pitfall 1: Using parentheses
Common Pitfall 2: Mistaking == (equals) for = (assignment)
Common Pitfall 2: Forgetting braces ({})
Common Pitfall 2: Dangling else
Common Pitfall 2: Duplicate Code in Different Case

You can use Math.random() to obtain a random double value between 0.0 and 1.0, excluding 1.0

The logical operators !, &&, ||, and ^ (EXCLUSIVE OR) can be used to create compound Boolean expressions
-  ! (NOT) Logical Negation
- && (AND) Logical Conjunction
- ||  (OR) Logical Disjunction
-  ^ (XOR) Logical Exclusion

Truth Table for Operator && (AND)
false && false = false
false && true  = false
true  && true  = true

Truth Table for Operator || (OR)
false || false = false
false || true  = true
true  || true  = true

Truth Table for Operator ^ (XOR)
false ^ false = false
false ^ true  = true
true  ^ true  = false

Truth Table for Operator ! (NOT)
false ! false = true
false ! true  = false
true  ! true  = true

A switch statement executes statements based on the value of a variable or an expression

The switch statement observes the following rules:
- The switch-expression must yield a value of char, byte, short, int, or String type
  and must always be enclosed in parentheses
- The value1, ..., and valueN must have the same data type as the value of the
  switch expression
- When the value in a case statement matches the value of the switch expression
- The default case, which is optional, can be used to perform actions when none of the
  specified cases matches the switch-expression
- The keyword break is optional and immediately ends the switch statement

A conditional operator evaluates an expression based on a condition

Ex. if (x > 0) {    // boolean-expression ? expression1 : expression2;
        y = 1;      // Tertiary Operator
    } else {
        y = -1;     // y = (x > 0) ? 1 : -1;
    }               // y = (x > 0) ? 1 OR -1;

Ex. System.out.println((num % 2 == 0) ? "num is even" : "num is odd");

Operator precedence and associativity determine the rder in which operators are evaluated...
var++ and var-- (Postfix)
+, -, (Unary plus/minus) ++var and --var (Prefix)
(type) Casting
!(Not)
*, /, %
+, - (Binary addition/subtraction)
Relational

Left associativity (left to right) ->
Ex. a - b + c - d
    ((a - b) + c) - d // 0

Right associativity (right to left) <-
Ex. a = b += c = 5
    a = (b += (c = 5)) // 6
